  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 14.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - From these external features the teacher passes to the heart the seat of all this mischief and deceit. In this respect we observe a striking correspondence with the method adopted by our Saviour in his leaching, who referred everything to the heart, as the true seat of all that was good or bad in man. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Frowardness is in his heart",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "tah'pukoth b'libbo",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " his heart is full of perverse imaginations, it is there he nourishes his jealousy, his hatred, his malice, his ill will. It is there, too, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "he deviseth mischief continually.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"Devising mischief\" carries us one step further back in the history of evil. It is this feature, this deliberate premeditation to plot mischief and to devise means to carry it into execution, which makes the character of the man simply diabolical. He makes his heart as it were the workshop wherein he fabricates and prepares his villainy. The Hebrew ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "kharash",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (to which the participle ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "khoresh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " belongs) is equivalent to the Vulgate ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "machinari",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the LXX. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τεκαίνομαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"to fabricate, devise, plot.\" (See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 3:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ver. 18; and cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 36:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"He deviseth mischief upon his bed.\") The LXX. combines the two statements in one proposition: \"A perverse heart deviseth evil at all  times.\" Similarly the Vulgate, which, however, joins \"continually\" (Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "b'koleth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Vulgate, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "omni tempore",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to the second hemistich, thus: \"And at all times he sows discord (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "et omni tempore jurgia seminat",
        "children": []
      },
      {
